#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
MKT Original — Haggai chapters 1–2 (all 38 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-haggai-1-2-full.py

Key translation/term decisions:
- simu levavkem (1:5,7; 2:15,18): "consider carefully" / "set your heart" — deliberate self-examination
- ha-am hazeh (1:2): "these people" — distanced language, YHWH not calling them "my people"
- batim sephunim (1:4): "paneled houses" — cedar-lined luxury rooms, not just "roofed"
- hemdah (2:7): "treasures" / "desired things" — disputed; Vulgate's "desideratus" (singular Messianic) is a later theological reading; MT verb is plural; MKT follows MT with "treasures of all nations"
- chotam (2:23): "signet ring" — directly reverses the curse of Jer 22:24 where Coniah was stripped like a signet
- od achat mea't (2:6): "yet once more, a little while" — Hebrews 12:26 cites this as inaugurating cosmic upheaval
- tsevaot: retained as "of Hosts" or "Almighty" in some verses — YHWH's epithet of cosmic command
- malak YHWH (1:13): "messenger of YHWH" — Haggai himself is called this, unique among writing prophets
- ruach (1:14; 2:5): "spirit" — YHWH stirs human spirit (1:14) and his own Spirit remains (2:5)
- shalom (2:9): "peace/shalom" — deliberately left as shalom to carry the full covenantal freight
"""

import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HAGGAI = {
    "1": {
        "1": '<p>The opening date formula is precise: "In the second year of King Darius, on the first day of the sixth month" — August 29, 520 BCE by modern reckoning. The prophet Haggai is called only <em>navi</em> (prophet), not given any genealogy or hometown; his identity is entirely functional. The word comes "by the hand of (<em>be-yad</em>) Haggai" — the standard formula for prophetic delivery, where the prophet is YHWH\'s instrument. The recipients are Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and Joshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest — the civil and cultic leaders of the returned community. Zerubbabel appears in Matthew\'s genealogy (Matt 1:12-13), grandson of Jehoiachin; Joshua is the high priest whose restoration is also the subject of Zechariah 3.</p>',
        "2": '<p>"These people" (<em>ha-am hazeh</em>) — not "my people" but "this people" — is YHWH\'s pointed distancing from a community that has set covenant obligations aside. The claim that "the time has not yet come to rebuild YHWH\'s house" (<em>lo-et-bo et-beit YHWH lehibanot</em>) uses the same word for the temple that will dominate the book. The delay is not theological but practical — the returned community prioritized their own comfort. The <em>et</em> (time/right time) they invoke as their excuse becomes, in YHWH\'s refutation, the <em>et</em> they had already found convenient for their own houses.</p>',
        "3": '<p>A brief transition verse: "Then the word of YHWH came by the hand of the prophet Haggai" — the formula is repeated from 1:1, reinforcing that what follows is not the prophet\'s editorial but a direct divine word. The short verses at transition points in Haggai serve as structural markers, dividing the book into five distinct oracles (1:1-11, 1:12-15, 2:1-9, 2:10-19, 2:20-23). The repetition of the delivery formula gives each oracle its own framing as an independent word.</p>',
        "4": '<p>The rhetorical question — "Is it time (<em>ha-et</em>) for you yourselves to be living in your paneled houses (<em>batim sephunim</em>) while this house lies in ruins (<em>charev</em>)?" — pairs two <em>et</em> (time) references: their claim that the time hasn\'t come for the temple, and YHWH\'s counter that they\'ve already found time for their own comfort. <em>Batim sephunim</em> means specifically cedar-paneled rooms — the luxury finishing Solomon used for the temple\'s inner rooms (1 Kgs 6:15). The returned community used temple-grade finishing for their own homes while leaving the temple itself in rubble (<em>charev</em> = desolate, as in a wasteland).</p>',
        "5": '<p>"So now this is what YHWH of Hosts says: Consider carefully your ways (<em>simu levavkem al-darkeikhem</em>)" — the literal Hebrew is "set your heart on your roads/paths." The phrase recurs at 1:7, 2:15, and 2:18, forming the book\'s characteristic refrain of self-examination. <em>Simu levavkem</em> (lit. "place your heart") calls for more than intellectual reflection — the <em>lev</em> (heart) in Hebrew is the seat of will and decision, not merely emotion. The command is to direct their full intentional attention to the pattern of their life. What have they actually been doing? What has it produced? The examination itself is the beginning of repentance.</p>',
        "6": '<p>The list of futilities catalogs the precise reversal of covenant blessing: "you have planted much but harvested little; you eat but never have enough; you drink but never have your fill; you clothe yourselves but no one is warm; and he who earns wages does so to put them into a bag with holes (<em>tseror naquv</em>)." The imagery of the bag with holes is vivid — every coin earned falls through before it can accumulate. This is the Deuteronomic covenant curse enacted in economic terms (Deut 28:38-40): labor produces nothing because the blessing that makes labor fruitful has been withdrawn. The community works but cannot accumulate; they harvest but cannot store.</p>',
        "7": '<p>The refrain returns: "This is what YHWH of Hosts says: Consider carefully your ways" (<em>simu levavkem al-darkeikhem</em>). The repetition after the list of futilities is rhetorical: having described the evidence, YHWH asks them to draw the conclusion themselves. The examination is not punitive but diagnostic — the community needs to recognize the pattern of cause and effect. Their inattention to YHWH\'s house is the cause; the economic futility is the effect. The <em>simu levavkem</em> formula invites them to make that connection rather than be told it.</p>',
        "8": '<p>The divine directive: "Go up to the mountain (<em>alah ha-har</em>), bring down timber (<em>etzim</em>), and build the house — so that I may take pleasure in it (<em>ve-ertseh bo</em>) and be glorified (<em>ve-ekaved</em>)." Three imperatives followed by divine purpose. The mountain is not specified — the hills around Jerusalem. The construction material is wood, not stone; the task is not the full temple project but getting it started. <em>Ertseh</em> (I will take pleasure/be pleased) uses the priestly vocabulary of divine acceptance — the same root as the &#x2018;acceptable year&#x2019; and sacrificial acceptance. <em>Ve-ekaved</em> (I will be glorified) — the temple is the vehicle of YHWH\'s <em>kavod</em> (glory/weight/presence).</p>',
        "9": '<p>"You looked for much, but behold it came to little; and when you brought it home, I blew it away (<em>nafachti vo</em>)." The image of YHWH blowing away their gathered harvest with a breath is sharply personal — not an impersonal economic force but direct divine action. The question that follows explains: "Because of my house, which lies in ruins (<em>charev</em>), while each of you runs to his own house (<em>beito</em>)." The wordplay between <em>beit YHWH</em> (YHWH\'s house) and <em>beito</em> (his own house) is exact: they rush to their own <em>beit</em> while YHWH\'s <em>beit</em> is <em>charev</em> (desolate). The covenant economy inverted.</p>',
        "10": '<p>"Therefore on account of you (<em>aleikhem</em>), the skies (<em>shamayim</em>) have held back the dew (<em>tal</em>), and the earth has held back its produce (<em>yevulah</em>)." The economic reversal in 1:6 is now explicitly traced to its source: not natural variability but covenantal consequence. YHWH commands creation to hold back the rain-dew cycle that makes agricultural life possible. <em>Aleikhem</em> places the responsibility squarely on them. The withholding is not punishment but consequence — the community that withholds what belongs to YHWH finds that YHWH withholds what belongs to them. The covenant works in both directions.</p>',
        "11": '<p>"And I decreed a drought (<em>chorev</em>) on the land and on the hills, on the grain, the new wine, and the oil — on all that the ground yields — on man and on cattle and on all the labor of hands (<em>yegiea kapayim</em>)." <em>Chorev</em> (drought/desolation) is the exact root as the <em>charev</em> (ruined/desolate) used of the temple in 1:4,9 — the drought-desolation (<em>chorev</em>) falls on the land because the house-desolation (<em>charev</em>) was allowed to continue. The wordplay is precise and deliberate: the form of the curse mirrors the form of the neglect. The comprehensive list — grain, wine, oil, humans, cattle, all labor — covers every category of covenant blessing from Deuteronomy 7:13 and 28:18.</p>',
        "12": '<p>"Then Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel and Joshua son of Jehozadak the high priest and all the remnant of the people (<em>kol she\'erit ha-am</em>) obeyed the voice of YHWH their God." The triple subject — governor, priest, all the remnant — indicates comprehensive covenant response. <em>She\'erit</em> (remnant) is the technical term for the surviving community of the exile; their obedience is the fulfillment of what the prophets had promised the remnant would eventually do. "And they feared before YHWH" (<em>va-yire\'u et-pnei YHWH</em>) — the fear is reverent awe at YHWH\'s word delivered through his messenger, not terror. This is the covenant <em>yirah</em> that is the beginning of wisdom and the seed of genuine worship.</p>',
        "13": '<p>"Then Haggai, the messenger of YHWH (<em>malak YHWH</em>), spoke the LORD\'s message to the people: \'I am with you (<em>ani itkem</em>), declares YHWH.\'" <em>Malak YHWH</em> (messenger/angel of YHWH) is the title used for the divine messenger in Genesis 16, Judges 6, etc. Haggai is the only writing prophet explicitly called <em>malak YHWH</em> — his prophetic function is elevated to the status of divine messenger. The content of the message is the entire covenant assurance in three words: <em>ani itkem</em> — "I am with you." This is the Immanuel formula (Isa 7:14; Matt 1:23) concentrated to its minimum: the divine presence accompanies those who return to covenant faithfulness.</p>',
        "14": '<p>"And YHWH stirred up (<em>va-yaar</em>) the spirit (<em>ruach</em>) of Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel... and the spirit of Joshua son of Jehozadak the high priest, and the spirit of all the remnant of the people." The divine initiative is explicit: YHWH does not merely command but moves the human will. <em>Va-yaar</em> (stirred/roused/awakened) — the same root describes the stirring of the east wind and the awakening from sleep. YHWH awakens what lay dormant in each of the three groups. The response in 1:12 is human obedience; the enablement in 1:14 is divine stirring. Both are true simultaneously — genuine human response that is enabled by divine initiative. "And they came and worked on the house of YHWH of Hosts."</p>',
        "15": '<p>The closing date of the first oracle: "on the twenty-fourth day of the sixth month, in the second year of King Darius." The first oracle began on the first day of the sixth month (1:1); work began twenty-three days later. The precision of the dates is a feature of Haggai unique among the prophetic books — every oracle is precisely dated, creating a calendar of covenant renewal. The dates allow reconstruction: the community moved from YHWH\'s word (1st of 6th month) to actual construction (24th of 6th month) in less than a month. The gap between hearing and doing was brief, which Haggai records as significant.</p>'
    },
    "2": {
        "1": '<p>"In the seventh month, on the twenty-first day of the month, the word of YHWH came by the hand of the prophet Haggai." The twenty-first day of the seventh month is the last full day of the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot) — the seven-day festival of ingathering and covenant renewal (Lev 23:33-43). The timing is not incidental: Tabernacles was also the festival at which Solomon dedicated the first temple (1 Kgs 8:2). YHWH chooses the final day of the feast — the day of greatest communal gathering and reflection — to address the community\'s discouragement about the modest size of the new building project.</p>',
        "2": '<p>The oracle is directed to the same three groups as before — Zerubbabel the governor, Joshua the high priest, and all the remnant of the people — who are addressed in 2:2 as "all the remnant of the people." The three-part address (governor, priest, people) reflects the full covenant community structure. Haggai is sent to speak to all of them, which suggests that the discouragement being addressed is not elite but universal — the entire community shares the sense that the new structure falls far short of Solomon\'s glory.</p>',
        "3": '<p>"Who among you is left (<em>ha-nishar</em>) who saw this house in its former glory (<em>be-chevdato ha-rishon</em>)? And how does it appear to you now? Is it not as nothing in your eyes (<em>ke-ayin</em>)?" The question has a precise demographic answer: the older returnees who had seen Solomon\'s temple before its destruction in 586 BCE — now survivors of more than sixty years of exile — could remember its glory. <em>Kevod</em> (glory/weight) is the term for the divine presence-manifestation; the former temple\'s <em>kevod</em> was architectural and divine simultaneously. The current project must look like nothing by comparison. YHWH names their grief honestly before addressing it.</p>',
        "4": '<p>"But now be strong, Zerubbabel (<em>chazaq Zerubbavel</em>)... be strong, Joshua son of Jehozadak... be strong, all you people of the land... and work (<em>va-asu</em>), for I am with you (<em>ki ani itkem</em>), declares YHWH of Hosts." <em>Chazaq</em> (be strong) is Joshua\'s commissioning word in Joshua 1:6,7,9 — the same three-fold strengthening given to the leader who must complete what Moses began. YHWH repeats it here to governor, priest, and people alike. The ground of the strength is identical to Joshua 1:9 and Haggai 1:13: <em>ani itkem</em> — "I am with you." The formula of divine presence is the only adequate resource for a community facing an overwhelming comparison.</p>',
        "5": '<p>"According to the word that I covenanted with you when you came out of Egypt, and my Spirit (<em>ruachi</em>) remains (<em>omedet</em>) among you — do not fear." The covenant with the Exodus generation is invoked as the ground of YHWH\'s present commitment: the same faithfulness that brought Israel through the sea remains operative in the returned community. <em>Ruachi omedet be-tokhechem</em> — "my Spirit stands in your midst" — <em>omedet</em> (standing, remaining, persisting) suggests permanence rather than a passing visitation. The Spirit that was with Israel in the wilderness continues with the returned community. The command "do not fear" (<em>al-tira\'u</em>) is based entirely on this double foundation: the past covenant and the present Spirit.</p>',
        "6": '<p>"For this is what YHWH of Hosts says: Yet once more, in a little while (<em>od achat mea\'t hi</em>), I will shake (<em>anishi</em>) the heavens and the earth and the sea and the dry land." <em>Od achat mea\'t hi</em> is literally "yet one, it is a little" — an idiom for "just a little while longer." <em>Anishi</em> (I will shake/cause to tremble) — the root <em>naash</em> describes violent earthquake-level shaking. The heavens, earth, sea, and dry land constitute the full cosmos; YHWH claims authority over every domain. Hebrews 12:26-27 cites this verse as the definitive announcement that the created order will be shaken to distinguish what is shakeable from what is not — the unshakeable kingdom.</p>',
        "7": '<p>"And I will shake all the nations, and they will come — the <em>hemdah</em> (treasures/desire) of all nations — and I will fill this house with glory (<em>kavod</em>), says YHWH of Hosts." <em>Hemdah</em> (Hag 2:7) is one of the most disputed words in the book: it can mean "desired thing," "treasure," or the abstract quality of desirability. The MT verb (<em>u-va\'u</em>) is plural — "they will come" — suggesting the subject is collective: the treasures of all nations streaming in. The Vulgate reads it as a singular Christological title (<em>desideratus cunctis gentibus</em>), a reading followed by many medieval commentators, but the Hebrew grammar does not require this. The promise is that YHWH will fill the new temple with the <em>kavod</em> — the glory-presence — that the community fears is absent.</p>',
        "8": '<p>"The silver is mine and the gold is mine (<em>li ha-kesev ve-li ha-zahav</em>), declares YHWH of Hosts." The divine claim over all material wealth addresses the community\'s practical concern: how can the new temple match Solomon\'s gold-covered structure when the returned community has almost nothing? YHWH\'s answer is that material shortage is not the limiting factor — everything belongs to him. This is simultaneously a claim about sovereignty (all wealth is YHWH\'s to deploy) and a rebuke of the assumption that human resource limits bound what YHWH can do. The temple\'s glory will not depend on the community\'s material capacity.</p>',
        "9": '<p>"The future glory of this house will be greater than the former (<em>gadol yihyeh kevod ha-bayit ha-zeh ha-acharon min ha-rishon</em>), says YHWH of Hosts. And in this place I will give shalom (<em>shalom</em>), declares YHWH of Hosts." The contrast is explicit: <em>ha-acharon</em> (the latter) will surpass <em>ha-rishon</em> (the former). The metric is <em>kavod</em> — the glory-presence that constitutes the temple\'s essence. The latter glory is not measured in gold or architectural grandeur but in divine presence. The oracle closes with <em>shalom</em> — the comprehensive covenant welfare: peace, wholeness, restored relationship. This is the promise to the community whose present experience is economic futility and discouragement.</p>',
        "10": '<p>"On the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month, in the second year of Darius, the word of YHWH came to the prophet Haggai." The fourth oracle is precisely dated: December 18, 520 BCE — exactly three months after the first oracle (Sixth month, day 1) and on the same day as the foundation-laying of the temple. The date is significant because 2:18 refers to "the day the LORD\'s temple foundation was laid" — and this oracle arrives on that very day, turning it into a day of blessing rather than merely construction. YHWH\'s word accompanies the physical act of rebuilding.</p>',
        "11": '<p>"This is what YHWH of Hosts says: Ask the priests for a ruling on the law (<em>shaalu-na et-ha-kohanim torah</em>)." <em>Torah</em> here is priestly instruction — the technical legal rulings that were a primary function of the priesthood (Deut 17:9-11; Lev 10:10-11). YHWH instructs Haggai to pose two test cases about holiness transmission, using the priestly ruling process as a pedagogical vehicle. The question-and-answer structure mimics the priestly <em>torah</em> process itself: presenting a case for authoritative adjudication. This is the only extended priestly legal dialogue in the minor prophets.</p>',
        "12": '<p>The first test case: "If someone carries holy meat (<em>basar qodesh</em>) in the fold of his garment and his garment touches bread, stew, wine, oil, or any other food — does it become holy?" The priests answer no. The point is that holiness is not transmitted by contact — the garment carrying holy meat cannot pass holiness to other foods it touches. This runs counter to popular assumption: being near the holy does not make things holy. Holiness requires direct consecration, not adjacency. The ruling is straightforward priestly law (Lev 6:27 concerns blood, but the principle is similar).</p>',
        "13": '<p>"Then Haggai said: If someone who is defiled by contact with a corpse (<em>tameh-nefesh</em>) touches any of these things, does it become defiled?" The priests answer yes. The second ruling reverses the direction: defilement is transmitted by contact in ways that holiness is not. The corpse-defiled person (<em>tameh-nefesh</em> — literally "defiled of soul/person" — Numbers 19:11,13 establishes this) makes everything he touches unclean. Uncleanness spreads; holiness does not. This asymmetry is the theological axiom YHWH is about to apply to the community.</p>',
        "14": '<p>"Then Haggai answered: That is exactly how this people and this nation are before me, declares YHWH — and so is everything the work of their hands, and what they offer there is defiled." <em>Ha-am hazeh ve-ha-goi hazeh</em> — "this people and this nation" — the double distancing phrase intensifies the alienation expressed in 1:2. The application of the priestly rulings: the community\'s defilement transmits to everything they do, including their sacrifices. The altar stood before the temple was rebuilt (Ezra 3:2-3), so sacrifices had been offered — but with a defiled community, the offerings themselves were defiled. The rebuilding is necessary precisely because holiness requires intentional pursuit, not mere proximity to religious activity.</p>',
        "15": '<p>"But now, consider carefully from this day forward (<em>simu na levavkem me-ha-yom hazeh va-maalah</em>): before one stone was placed upon another in the LORD\'s temple..." The <em>simu levavkem</em> refrain returns, but now with temporal precision — "from this day forward." The moment of the oracle (the foundation-laying day) is the hinge point: everything before today had the defilement-transmission problem; from today, a new trajectory begins. <em>Me-ha-yom hazeh va-maalah</em> — "from this day and upward" — creates a before-and-after structure in the community\'s covenant history.</p>',
        "16": '<p>"How did you fare? When someone came to a heap of grain expecting twenty measures (<em>esrim</em>), there were only ten (<em>asarah</em>); when one came to the vat to draw fifty measures of wine, there were only twenty." The 50% shortfall in grain and 60% shortfall in wine are the quantified expression of covenant curse — not total failure but persistent, inescapable shortfall. YHWH is describing what the community had been experiencing as economic bad luck as divine calibration: the numbers are not random but covenantally structured. The precision of the amounts — twenty expected/ten found; fifty expected/twenty found — gives the curse a kind of mathematical specificity.</p>',
        "17": '<p>"I struck you (<em>hiketi etkhem</em>) and all the products of your labor with blight (<em>shidafon</em>), mildew (<em>yerakon</em>), and hail (<em>barad</em>) — yet you did not return to me (<em>ve-einchem elai</em>), declares YHWH." The three agricultural disasters — blight, mildew, hail — are the Deuteronomic covenant curses cataloged in Deuteronomy 28:22 and Amos 4:9. YHWH is identifying his own hand in what the community had presumably treated as agricultural misfortune. The stunning conclusion: "yet you did not return to me" — despite the repeated evidence of covenant consequences, the community had not recognized the pattern or drawn the covenantal conclusion. <em>Ve-einchem elai</em> — "and you were not to me" — the relational rupture behind the economic failure.</p>',
        "18": '<p>"Consider carefully from this day on — the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month — from the day the LORD\'s temple foundation was laid, consider carefully." The <em>simu levavkem</em> formula appears twice in this verse, framing the date of the foundation-laying as the decisive transition point. The date repetition — "from this day on" and "from the day the foundation was laid" — is redundant unless the oracle arrives on the very day of the foundation-laying, making the day simultaneously the date of the blessing and the date of its announcement. YHWH\'s word and the physical act of rebuilding coincide on the same calendar day.</p>',
        "19": '<p>"Is the seed still in the granary? And as for the vine, the fig tree, the pomegranate, and the olive tree — they have not yet borne fruit. But from this day I will bless you (<em>me-ha-yom hazeh avarekh</em>)." The rhetorical question about the granary acknowledges that the physical situation has not yet changed — no seed has sprouted, no tree has fruited, nothing looks different yet. The blessing is announced before the evidence appears. <em>Me-ha-yom hazeh avarekh</em> — "from this day I will bless" — is unconditional and effective: YHWH\'s declaration of blessing creates the reality it announces. The specific mention of vine, fig tree, pomegranate, and olive tree covers the full range of covenant agricultural blessing from Deuteronomy.</p>',
        "20": '<p>"The word of YHWH came a second time to Haggai on the twenty-fourth day of the month." The fifth and final oracle arrives on the same day as the fourth (2:10,18 — the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month), making two oracles on the same date. The brief transition notation separates them clearly: what follows is a new divine word, not a continuation of the blessing oracle. The "second time" (<em>shenit</em>) on the same day makes this the most concentrated pair of oracles in the book — two distinct words from YHWH within a single calendar day.</p>',
        "21": '<p>"Speak to Zerubbabel, governor of Judah, saying: I am about to shake (<em>anishi</em>) the heavens and the earth." The cosmic shaking of 2:6 is repeated but now narrowed to a single addressee: Zerubbabel alone. The first shaking oracle (2:6-9) was addressed to the full community; this oracle is personal and dynastic. The shaking formula (<em>anishi et-hashamayim ve-et-ha\'aretz</em>) is identical — YHWH\'s authority over the entire cosmic order. The purpose of repeating it to Zerubbabel alone becomes clear in the verses that follow: the cosmic shaking has personal implications for this specific man from the Davidic line.</p>',
        "22": '<p>"I will overturn the throne of kingdoms (<em>ve-hafachti kisse mamlakot</em>) and destroy the power of the kingdoms of the nations (<em>chazaq mamlekot ha-goyim</em>). I will overturn chariots and their riders — the horses and their riders will fall, each by his brother\'s sword (<em>ish be-cherev achiv</em>)." The military imagery is total: thrones overturned, power destroyed, chariots and cavalry fallen — and falling by mutual slaughter (<em>ish be-cherev achiv</em>, "each by his brother\'s sword"). The same formula of mutual self-destruction appears in Judges 7:22 (Gideon\'s battle) and Ezekiel 38:21 — YHWH\'s defeat of enemy powers by turning them against each other. No external army is needed; the imperial powers collapse from within.</p>',
        "23": '<p>"On that day (<em>ba-yom ha-hu</em>), declares YHWH of Hosts, I will take you, Zerubbabel my servant (<em>avdi</em>) son of Shealtiel, and make you like a signet ring (<em>chotam</em>), for I have chosen you (<em>becharti becha</em>), declares YHWH of Hosts." <em>Ba-yom ha-hu</em> — the eschatological "that day" formula — lifts the promise beyond historical-political restoration toward messianic horizon. Three terms of covenant election: <em>avdi</em> (my servant) — the title of David, Moses, and the Servant of YHWH in Isaiah; <em>chotam</em> (signet ring) — the reversal of Jeremiah 22:24 where Coniah was stripped off as a signet ring, now Zerubbabel the grandson is re-invested with dynastic authority; <em>becharti</em> (I have chosen) — the election vocabulary of the Davidic covenant. YHWH does not name Zerubbabel king, but names him with every term that carries royal-messianic weight — signet ring, servant, chosen — pointing through him toward the one who will fulfill these promises completely.</p>'
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'haggai')
    merge_comm(existing, HAGGAI)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'haggai', existing)
    print('Haggai 1-2 mkt-original written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
